<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96947149028494></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96947149028494><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=2&mid=96947149028494>RE: Rogue Discussion</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=2&mid=96947149028494#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1250><span id= >Dagis</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Sep 20th 1:38 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>At level 10 you get backstab, it is a SKILL like sneak or hide. When you activate it, it has a recycle time it has to complete before you can use it again. When using your backstab skill, you nead to be in the REAR ARC of the mob, that's the 180 degrees behind the mob. This includes if you get just behind the mobs arm too, we're talking full back arc. Then you will backstab. If you use backstab when in the front arc, you will just use it as an extra pierce attack, and you will not have a chance at skill gain. Backstab is a piercing weapon skill only, so when you're going to backstab, make sure you have a piercing weapon in you PRIMARY hand. Also a good tip is that since the skill raises so slowly and you'll want it to raise quickly is to save training points for level 10 to put into your backstab skill.<br><br>As for races, pick what you want to play :)<br><br>Strength WILL make a difference in your backstab, but only a few points of damage really, it is NOTHING you need to worry about for character creation. Just pick your favorite race, then (SUGGESTED) for placing your bonus points is to dump 25 points into strength and the other 5 into dex, for max combat effect.  I HOPE that you are choosing between those two classes because you're interested in playing the race, not because of the strength. Here's a fun thing to note: Verant has balanced the races in character creation so well because physical statistics are basically crap. A small boost to any statistic won't do too much. Besides that, because of different armors' bonuses and stat jewelry, you're really pretty well able to customize the stats that you're interested in. Popular opinion is that you want ac, hp, and strength for melees as your primary goal, in that order. But, again don't worry about strength  it arguably doesn't matter that much, or any other stats (just make sure your agility is above 75, below that is a large ac hit and below 70 is where you start to slow down, easy for rogues to handle since they all start out with +75 agility but just something to be aware of if you're encumbered) that you can't play, say a dark elf (with de as an example because of the low strength) if you wanted to. Play what race you want to play and worry about stats later :)  (but as a midget lover i have to make a pull for dwarf, they do somersaults when they jump while running! acrobatics routines while waiting on a boat can be a great time killer, not to mention gives your character a great roleplay excuse to consume massive amounts of ale)<br><br>Dagis<br>Often imitated, frequently duplicated, but never cloned ;P<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
